    "cards": [
      {
        "id": "theory-card-1",
        "title": "Questions",
        "subtitle": "Questions",
        "cardType": "rule_card",
        "sections": [
          {
            "type": "comparison_table",
            "title": "Compare",
            "headers": [
              "Form",
              ""
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "With *be* as a main verb",
                "**Am**/**Was** I on time?\n**Are**/**Were** you/we/they ready to leave?\n**Is**/**Was** he/she/it the right answer?"
              ],
              [
                "With *be* as an auxiliary verb",
                "**Am**/**Was** I **bothering** you?\n**Are**/**Were** you/we/they **coming** to the event?\n**Is**/**Was** he/she/it **staying** for dinner?"
              ],
              [
                "With *have* as an auxiliary verb",
                "**Have**/**Had** I/you/we/they packed everything?\n**Has**/**Had** he/she/it received the message?"
              ],
              [
                "With *have* as a main verb and with all other verbs",
                "**Do**/**Did** I/you/we/they have enough information?\n**Does**/**Did** he/she/it know the answer?"
              ],
              [
                "With modals",
                "**Should** I turn right here?\n**Could** you lend me your notes?\n**Will** she be there on time?\n**Might** they be lost?"
              ],
              [
                "With *who, whose, whom, what, which, where, when, why* and *how*",
                "**Who** is running the project?\n**Whose** bag is this?\nTo **whom** should I give the form?\n**What** is the plan for tomorrow?\n**Which** would you prefer?\n**Where** did they spend their holiday?\n**When** is Clara starting her new job?\n**Why** did they cancel the match?\n**How** do you say 'ticket' in Italian?"
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "remember_box",
            "title": "Be careful",
            "items": [
              {
                "note": "With the question words *who* and *what*, whether you need *do* or not depends on whether the question word is the **subject** or the **object** of the sentence."
              },
              {
                "correct": "Subject: *Who **called** you last night?* (= Someone called you. Who was it?)"
              },
              {
                "correct": "Object: *Who **did** you **call** last night?* (= You called someone. Who did you call?)"
              },
              {
                "note": "After *do* or *does*, always use the bare infinitive — not the past form or a conjugated form."
              },
              {
                "correct": "*Did you **go** to the concert?*"
              },
              {
                "incorrect": "*Did you **went** to the concert?*"
              },
              {
                "correct": "*Does he **want** a coffee?*"
              },
              {
                "incorrect": "*Does he **wants** a coffee?*"
              },
              {
                "note": "The verb *mean* follows the same question pattern as other ordinary verbs."
              },
              {
                "correct": "*What **does** 'procrastinate' **mean**?*"
              },
              {
                "incorrect": "*What **means** 'procrastinate'?*"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "theory-card-2",
        "title": "Question tags",
        "subtitle": "Question tags",
        "cardType": "rule_card",
        "sections": [
          {
            "type": "comparison_table",
            "title": "Compare",
            "headers": [
              "Form",
              ""
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "With *be* as a main verb",
                "You **are** from Brazil, **aren't** you?\nShe **is** a nurse, **isn't** she?"
              ],
              [
                "With auxiliary verbs and modals",
                "You **haven't** seen my phone, **have** you?\nWe **are** meeting tomorrow morning, **aren't** we?\nPeople **should** recycle more, **shouldn't** they?\nThere **will** be enough seats, **won't** there?"
              ],
              [
                "With *have* as a main verb",
                "Tom **has** a great sense of humour, **hasn't**/**doesn't** he?"
              ],
              [
                "With other verbs",
                "You like jazz, **don't** you?\nEmma works in the city centre now, **doesn't** she?\nYour friends really enjoyed the trip, **didn't** they?"
              ],
              [
                "With *Let's*",
                "Let's get some fresh air, **shall** we?"
              ],
              [
                "With imperatives",
                "Pass me that pen, **will**/**would**/**could** you?\nDon't forget to lock up, **will** you?"
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "bullet_list",
            "title": "Use",
            "items": [
              "To invite someone to agree with us (falling intonation): *The weather is lovely today, **isn't** it?*",
              "To check whether something is true (rising intonation): *You've been here before, **haven't** you?*"
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "remember_box",
            "title": "Be careful",
            "items": [
              {
                "note": "After *I am*, the question tag is *aren't I?* After *I am not*, the question tag is *am I?*"
              },
              {
                "correct": "I'm the last one to arrive, **aren't** I?"
              },
              {
                "correct": "I'm not very punctual, **am** I?"
              },
              {
                "note": "With *everyone*, *no one* and *someone*, we use a plural verb and *they* in the question tag."
              },
              {
                "correct": "Everyone enjoyed the party, **didn't** they?"
              },
              {
                "correct": "No one told you, **did** they?"
              },
              {
                "correct": "Someone borrowed my pen, **didn't** they?"
              },
              {
                "note": "A positive main clause normally takes a negative question tag, and vice versa. When the main clause contains a negative word like *no, never, hardly, nobody*, we use a positive question tag."
              },
              {
                "correct": "She **never** replies to messages, **does** she?"
              },
              {
                "correct": "There's **no** milk left, **is** there?"
              },
              {
                "note": "When the subject is *there*, we also use *there* in the question tag."
              },
              {
                "correct": "There's nothing to worry about, **is there**?"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "explanation",
            "title": "American English note",
            "description": "American English sometimes uses *do* in a question tag after a sentence with *have got*, which is not the usual pattern in British English."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "theory-card-3",
        "title": "Indirect questions",
        "subtitle": "Indirect questions",
        "cardType": "rule_card",
        "sections": [
          {
            "type": "explanation",
            "title": "Use",
            "description": "We use indirect questions to ask for information in a more polite or formal way."
          },
          {
            "type": "comparison_table",
            "title": "Compare",
            "headers": [
              "Some introductory phrases and questions",
              "Example"
            ],
            "rows": [
              [
                "*Can/Could you tell me ...?*",
                "*Could you tell me where the nearest pharmacy is?*"
              ],
              [
                "*Could you let me know ...?*",
                "*Could you let me know when the next flight departs?*"
              ],
              [
                "*Do you know ...?*",
                "*Do you know what time the museum opens?*"
              ],
              [
                "*I wonder if you could tell me ...*",
                "*I wonder if you could tell me how much this costs.*"
              ],
              [
                "*I wonder if you know ...*",
                "*I wonder if you know what the closing date is.*"
              ],
              [
                "*I would like to know ...*",
                "*I would like to know what the next steps are.*"
              ]
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "remember_box",
            "title": "Be careful",
            "items": [
              {
                "note": "The second part of an indirect question uses **normal statement word order** — not question word order."
              },
              {
                "correct": "Could you tell me where **the post office is**?"
              },
              {
                "incorrect": "Could you tell me where **is the post office**?"
              },
              {
                "note": "Some indirect questions starting with a question word still end with a question mark."
              },
              {
                "correct": "***Could** you tell me where the exit is?*"
              },
              {
                "note": "When a direct yes/no question becomes indirect, use *if* or *whether* to introduce the clause."
              },
              {
                "correct": "I wonder ***if***/**whether** the shop is still open."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
